The encoding-decoding procedure is described as follows. Transmitter i maps a message m i ∈ {1, 2, · · · , 2 nR i } into a length n codeword X n i that belongs to a codebook C n i , i.e. X n i = f n i (m i ), where f n i (.) represents the encoding function of user i, i = 1, 2, · · · , K. Codeword X n i is then sent over a block of n time instances. From the received sequence Y n i , receiver i obtains an estimate ˆ m i of the transmit message m i using a decoding function g n i (.), i.e. ˆ m i = g n i (Y n i ). The average probability of error is deﬁned as P n e = E [Pr(∪( ˆ m i ̸= m i ))]. A rate tuple (R 1 , R 2 , · · · , R K ) is said to be achievable if for an ϵ > 0, there exists a family of codebooks C n i , encoding functions f n i (.), and decoding functions g n i (.), i = 1, 2, · · · , K, such that P n e < ϵ for a sufﬁciently large n. The capacity region is the collection of all achievable rate tuples.
